sub_title: Marie Skłodowska-Curie ESR for MonPlas | PhD Candidate at Wageningen University and Research | Analysis of micro- and nano-plastics
summary:
MSc in Food Science and Human Nutrition captivated by Analytical Chemistry. 

I work on the development and validation of analytical methods for the characterization of microplastics and nanoplastics in food.

Aming to bring Analytical Chemistry to the forefront of microplastic and nanoplastic research.

projects:
[{'title': 'ABACUS', 'date': {'start': {'month': 3, 'day': None, 'year': 2019}, 'end': {'month': 9, 'day': None, 'year': 2019}}, 'description': 'The ABACUS project – Algae for a Biomass Applied to the produCtion of added valUe compoundS –  aims to develop an innovative algal biorefinery for the synthesis of high-value bio-based chemicals. 
In particular, the project is focused on the production of terpenes and terpenoids as competitive ingredients in pharmaceutical, nutraceutical, cosmetic and food industries. 
Through its interdisciplinary approach, ABACUS also purposes to identify markets for secondary products, to assess the environmental impact of the production line and to evaluate the market acceptance of the final goods. 

I took part in the ABACUS project as part of my master thesis work, which I realized at the Institute of Food Science Research (CIAL, UAM-CSIC). 
I was asked to develop, under the supervision of the Foodomics group, a green method for the selective extraction of carotenoids from Dunaliella salina by means of compressed fluids. 

Thanks to an experimental design, I studied the effect of pressure and temperature on sub- and supercritical carbone dioxide extraction. Then, I carried out the qualitative and quantitative analysis of the resulting extracts by high performance liquid chromatography coupled with UV/Vis spectroscopy. 

Based on the obtained data, three mathematical models were designed to predict the extraction efficiency and selectivity. 
Comparison with a conventional solvent extraction proved the investigated green method to be superior in terms of purity, and, under certain conditions, also in terms of efficiency.

Bueno, M.; Vitali, C.; Sánchez-Martínez, J.D.; Gallego, R.; Mendiola, J.A.; Herrero, M.; Ibáñez, E. Experimental optimization of sub- and supercritical carbon dioxide extractions of carotenoids from Dunaliella salina. 1er Encuentro Ibérico de Fluidos Supercríticos, 18-19 February 2020, Santiago de Compostela, Spain.', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Clementina', 'last_name': 'Vitali', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Marie Skłodowska-Curie ESR for MonPlas | PhD Candidate at Wageningen University and Research | Analysis of micro- and nano-plastics'}]}, {'title': 'Characterization of phenolic compounds in juices, pulps, peels and seeds of seven Italian pomegranate cultivars by means of RF-HPLC/PDA/MS', 'date': {'start': {'month': 2, 'day': None, 'year': 2017}, 'end': {'month': 3, 'day': None, 'year': 2017}}, 'description': 'The aim of the project was the analysis of phenolic compounds in pomegranate juice and in the by-products of its industrial transformation: pulp, peel and seeds. Due to their strong antioxidant activity, poliphenols are competitive ingredients for pharmaceutical, nutraceutical, cosmetic and food industry and could turn those wastes into a source of high-value chemicals.

A method for the analysis of phenolic compounds from pomegranates was developed and validated. The characterization of the phenolic extract was carried out by the means of high performance liquid chromatography coupled with UV/Vis spectroscopy and mass spectrometry; total polyphenols and antioxidant activity were assesed by spectrophotometric assays. 

Differences in phenolic compound profiles among the pomegranate parts were observed: peels showed the highest concentration of phenolic compounds, ellagitannins being the most abundant ones.

The project was presented at the 45th International Symposium on High Performance Liquid Phase Separations and Related Techniques and gave birth to a scientific publication.

Russo M., Tripodo G., Vitali C., Dugo P., Muleo R., Zecchini M., Mondello L., Fanali C., De Gara L., Characterization of phenolic compounds in juices, pulps, peels and seeds of seven Italian pomegranate cultivars by means of RP-HPLC/PDA/MS, 45th International Symposium on High Performance Liquid Phase Separations and Related Techniques (HPLC 2017 Prague), 18 - 22 June 2017, Prague, Czech Republic.
